[Student "S"]
{Make a choice. With 20 points you are strong enough to open 2NT. But, with two doubletons you can't really call this a balanced hand. So you should open 1\S.

Partner responds 2\S.  

There should be no doubt about this bid. Partner has at least 6 points so you know there is enough for game. You bid 4\S.

East plays 4\S. South leads \HA, \HK, \H3 and North follows to all three.

<b>East plays 4\S. South leads \HA, \HK, \H3 and North follows to all three.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 2 : \D 2 : \C 1 : Total = 5

The 5 loser count isn't actually right because at this point you can dump one of those losers on dummy's \HQ. The question is: Which one?

You have two chances to set up an extra winner - if the \Ds split 3-2 or if the \CK is with North. If you discard the \CQ right now you will be pinning all your hopes on the \D split. By discarding a \D instead you keep both possibilities alive.

So discard the \D. Pull trumps with \S A J (it takes two rounds) then play \DA and \DK. Bad news, North shows out. So now you take your second chance. Enter dummy with a trump and play a \C, finessing North for the \CK. Good news, this works. Two chances are better than one.

You might have thought it was better to discard the \CQ rather than a \D because the \C finesse was only a 50% chance while the chance of a 3-2 \D split was much better than that. 

The percentages are right but the logic is wrong. If you are going to benefit from a 3-2 \D split it is only necessary for you to keep 4 \Ds in <b>one</b> of the hands, not both. So the fourth \D in your hand was unimportant while the \CQ gave you an extra shot.}
[Play "W"]HA

